summary:
The Security Council,
Recalling previous resolutions on Sierra Leone, 
Affirming commitment to respect Sierra Leone's sovereignty, 
Welcoming progress in the peace process, 
Concerned about the illicit diamond trade's role in the conflict, 
Welcoming efforts to break the link between illicit diamonds and conflict, 
Determining the situation in Sierra Leone remains a threat to regional peace and security, 
Acting under Chapter VII, 
1. Welcomes the Certificate of Origin regime for diamond trade in Sierra Leone; 
2. Welcomes reports that the regime is curbing conflict diamonds; 
3. Extends measures imposed by resolution 1306 (2000) for 11 months from 5 January 2002, 
except for rough diamonds controlled by the Government under the Certificate of Origin regime; 
4. Decides to terminate these measures if the Council deems it appropriate; 
5. Requests the Secretary-General to publicize this resolution; 
6. Decides to remain seized of the matter.
